Netflix is tiptoeing so carefully around the talent compensation issue that=
 its executives must have seemed like Russian ballerinas at Tuesday=E2=80=
=99s presentation for agents, managers, and even a few publicists. The reps=
 all schlepped to the company=E2=80=99s Hollywood HQ for what=E2=80=94thank=
s to an erroneous trade report=E2=80=94was rumored to be the big unveiling =
of the controversial plan to switch from upfront buyouts for stars and crea=
tors to a combination of fees and contingent, unguaranteed compensation. In=
stead, Netflix chief content officer Bela Bajaria and her team basically br=
agged for an hour about the power of the platform and repeated the what=E2=
=80=99s-a-hit and how-we-market speeches they=E2=80=99ve given before, all =
while attempting to explain to the sellers what makes something a =E2=80=9C=
Netflix=E2=80=9D project. (Answer: pretty much everything.)

The
coffee was decent, but many people left disappointed, at least according to=
 those I=E2=80=99ve surveyed, though Netflix insists it has received very p=
ositive feedback. I know, imagine that=E2=80=94professional salespeople com=
plimenting the town=E2=80=99s biggest buyer to that buyer=E2=80=99s face. W=
hatever. This event almost certainly could have been an email.

What Netflix should have articulated to this group, and what=E2=80=99s bein=
g actively strategized inside the company, is a rationale for why the talen=
t community should willingly take less money up front in order to sustain N=
etflix and the streaming industry long term. From Netflix=E2=80=99s perspec=
tive, when every project is treated like a hit=E2=80=94and talent in little=
-watched shows and movies are paid like they=E2=80=99re Millie Bobby F-ing =
Brown=E2=80=94the company is incentivized to ultimately make fewer shows an=
d movies. Everyone knows this, they argue, because it=E2=80=99s how the fil=
m and television business worked for
decades before Netflix and a mountain of cheap debt upended that model. Co-=
C.E.O. Ted Sarandos overpaid talent up front as a tax on breaking into the =
clubby Hollywood oligarchy.

But now that Netflix has been accepted into the club and Ted has become its=
 gavel-wielding president, it=E2=80=99s time to revert at least somewhat ba=
ck to what worked perfectly well for all those years. After all, the $100 m=
illion showrunner deal didn=E2=80=99t exist 15 years ago. Chuck Lorre, J.J.=
 Abrams, Ryan Murphy=E2=80=94they basically capped out at $4 million to $6 =
million per year. But the upside was massive, potentially hundreds of milli=
ons of dollars in success. Now, Netflix is saying, You can=E2=80=99t get $2=
5 million per year with no incentive to produce popular programming, and yo=
u also can=E2=80=99t enjoy the upside that comes with popular programming i=
f you=E2=80=99re already making $25 million a year.

That=E2=80=99s at least the thinking. To many, it=E2=80=99s just a
money grab by a company now worth more than $300 billion=E2=80=94a pure fle=
x. Netflix is so much bigger than rivals and is making far more shows and m=
ovies, so it has both the incentive and, importantly, the ability to push c=
osts down. That=E2=80=99s why Sarandos is preaching ratings =E2=80=9Ctransp=
arency,=E2=80=9D as I wrote ( https://puck.news/netflix-is-all-about-transp=
arency-now/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F26%2F24%=
29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F26%2F24%29&utm_med=
ium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )=
 last week. And if that means offering a few big backend payouts down the l=
ine, it=E2=80=99s a small price to pay for no longer subsidizing the whiffs=
 that populate the lower end of the semi-annual Engagement Reports. And, of=
 course, shutting up the agents behind those whiffs.

So far, the new contingent compensation system has been deployed only on a =
few film projects. The talent get their fees like usual, but instead of a
buyout of backend there is a contingent element. The ultimate result is tha=
t the star or filmmaker agrees to take, say, 80 cents on the dollar, and if=
 the project hits a certain number of =E2=80=9Cviews=E2=80=9D (defined simi=
larly to what the guilds got in their recent deal, which is a hurdle above =
what the average Netflix project delivers), the participant gets back 40 ce=
nts on those 20 cents they gave up=E2=80=94or possibly more in great succes=
s.

As I=E2=80=99ve written, the new head of business affairs for the film divi=
sion, Jun Oh, and the Netflix contingent compensation strategy team (yes, t=
hat=E2=80=99s a thing), have a goal of eventually expanding it elsewhere=E2=
=80=94and, crucially, to get the town on board. But it=E2=80=99s clearly de=
signed to reduce costs, which prompted Endeavor C.E.O. Ari Emanuel to inele=
gantly joke with Bajaria in front of everyone on Tuesday, =E2=80=9CWhen are=
 you gonna talk about backend and how you=E2=80=99re gonna fuck us?=E2=80=
=9D

Agents of Change

That line generated laughs in the room, but Ari=E2=80=99s not wrong about t=
he widespread anxiety around town. Hollywood created the Netflix monster, a=
nd it=E2=80=99s now big enough to run roughshod. To that end, in the Netfli=
x view, the talent agencies and their own incentives are actually part of t=
he problem here. Let=E2=80=99s say, for example, Netflix offers a TV creato=
r a three-year, $100 million overall deal with no backend, or a three year,=
 $50 million overall deal with potentially another $150 million to be paid =
in backend for hit shows over the next 10 to 15 years. Which path do you th=
ink the agent would push the client to take?

The former, probably, right? That=E2=80=99s even if the agent believes stro=
ngly that the creator is super-talented and would ultimately see that $150 =
million. Why? Because the $100 million in guaranteed cash is
commissionable to the agent now, not over a decade and a half. It used to b=
e that individual agents who packaged or commissioned hit shows would often=
 continue to receive their cut of the fees even if they retired or left the=
 agency. In fact, the Big Three talent shops are still paying people who ha=
ven=E2=80=99t worked there in decades. Early Endeavor partners still make m=
oney from That =E2=80=9970s Show. Bob Broder drank for decades from the Chu=
ck Lorre trough.

But these days, packaging fees have been outlawed by the Writers Guild, and=
 the big agencies make it very difficult for agents to continue getting pai=
d on their deals once they retire or leave. When Margot Robbie=E2=80=99s ag=
ent left CAA, Margot and the Barbie money remained. So=E2=80=A6 these agent=
s are better off getting upfront cash sooner rather than later, even if the=
 later payout might be significantly larger. For years, Netflix and then th=
e other streamers and studios
have been happy to oblige. But now?

So, the thinking goes, the ultimate resolution requires agencies to change =
how they treat their own people. If Ari, Bryan Lourd at CAA, and the UTA gu=
ys let agents leave without financial sacrifices, they=E2=80=99d help Netfl=
ix and the others build a larger, more sustainable model that would allow c=
reators=E2=80=94and, thus, the agencies that represent them=E2=80=94to make=
 more money in the long term. Yes, it benefits Netflix, but it ultimately b=
enefits everyone.

Before you email me, I know there are holes in this argument. Top agents=E2=
=80=94the ones who dictate agency policy at the shops that are big enough t=
o influence Netflix=E2=80=94would argue that the client decides whether to =
bet on him or herself, not the agent. And the long-term health of the agenc=
y business requires agents to deliver honest advice, not indulge in self-in=
terested money grabs. Most of the best reps, in my experience, do encourage=
 clients
to be entrepreneurial. One of the big gripes about Netflix is that execs wa=
nt to change the compensation structure but not the controls=E2=80=94Netfli=
x still wants to hoard a series for the run of the show plus 10 years, whic=
h is a big value-suck from a production company that could exploit a show m=
any ways under the old model. In addition, for shows that come from outside=
 studios, those license fees are not currently performance-based. So, the c=
ost-plus premium for Lincoln Lawyer or Wednesday would need to rise just li=
ke the talent fees/backend if this system is gonna work.

But=E2=80=A6 the Netflix folks have a point. The current buyout structure h=
as delivered huge and immediate bonuses to these agencies. Look at Wolfs at=
 Apple TV+. Paying George Clooney and Brad Pitt more than $35 million each =
for a light crime caper (sorry, but I believe the Times=E2=80=99s salary re=
porting, not Clooney=E2=80=99s limp denial), and filmmaker Jon Watts
another $15 million, delivered CAA, which reps all three, a fat $8.5 millio=
n commission up front on one project, assuming they all pay the standard 10=
 percent (a big assumption these days). Waiting on the backend for that one=
 would have been a question=E2=80=94one that Lourd is rich and strategic en=
ough to wait out, of course, but the more-junior people on the team? Maybe =
less so.

Netflix (and, to a lesser extent, the others) could just strong-arm the age=
ncies into accepting an =E2=80=9Cevolution=E2=80=9D of deals, which sounds =
like what may happen. Given the precarious state of the entire entertainmen=
t economy, why would anyone voluntarily wait on anything these days? So thi=
s is gonna be a fight. Thus, the need for Netflix to better articulate clea=
rly the why behind it all.

That=E2=80=99s happening behind the scenes somewhat. But semi-public presen=
tations matter, too. If this is part of a plan to save the streaming busine=
ss, they should say so. If Netflix
believes the ultimate payouts will be greater in the aggregate, then their =
executives need to explain how. Does the talent community actually prefer a=
 cash business or an asset-creation business? Good question. Tuesday=E2=80=
=99s summit would have been a great place to further that dialogue.

See you Monday,
Matt

