          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Netflix is tiptoein=
g so carefully around the talent compensation issue that its executives mus=
t have seemed like Russian ballerinas at Tuesday=E2=80=99s presentation for=
 agents, managers, and even a few publicists. The reps all schlepped to the=
 company=E2=80=99s Hollywood HQ for what=E2=80=94thanks to an erroneous tra=
de report=E2=80=94was rumored to be the big unveiling of the controversial =
plan to switch from upfront buyouts for stars and creators to a combination=
 of fees and contingent, <i>unguaranteed</i> compensation. Instead, Netflix=
 chief content officer <b>Bela Bajaria</b> and her team basically bragged f=
or an hour about the power of the platform and repeated the what=E2=80=99s-=
a-hit and how-we-market speeches they=E2=80=99ve given before, all while at=
tempting to explain to the sellers what makes something a =E2=80=9CNetflix=
=E2=80=9D project. (Answer: pretty much everything.)<br/> <br/>The
coffee was decent, but many people left disappointed, at least according to=
 those I=E2=80=99ve surveyed, though Netflix insists it has received <i>ver=
y positive </i>feedback. I know, imagine that=E2=80=94professional salespeo=
ple complimenting the town=E2=80=99s biggest buyer to that buyer=E2=80=99s =
face. Whatever. This event almost certainly could have been an email.<br/> =
<br/>What Netflix <i>should</i> have articulated to this group, and what=E2=
=80=99s being actively strategized inside the company, is a rationale for <=
i>why</i> the talent community should willingly take less money up front in=
 order to sustain Netflix and the streaming industry long term. From Netfli=
x=E2=80=99s perspective, when every project is treated like a hit=E2=80=94a=
nd talent in little-watched shows and movies are paid like they=E2=80=99re =
<b>Millie Bobby F-ing Brown</b>=E2=80=94the company is incentivized to ulti=
mately make <i>fewer</i> shows and movies. Everyone knows this, they argue,=
 because it=E2=80=99s how the film and television business worked for
decades before Netflix and a mountain of cheap debt upended that model. Co-=
C.E.O. <b>Ted Sarandos</b> overpaid talent up front as a tax on breaking in=
to the clubby Hollywood oligarchy.<br/> <br/>But now that Netflix has been =
accepted into the club and Ted has become its gavel-wielding president, it=
=E2=80=99s time to revert at least <i>somewhat</i> back to what worked perf=
ectly well for all those years. After all, the $100 million showrunner deal=
 didn=E2=80=99t exist 15 years ago. <b>Chuck Lorre</b>, <b>J.J. Abrams</b>,=
 <b>Ryan Murphy</b>=E2=80=94they basically capped out at $4 million to $6 m=
illion per year. But the upside was massive, potentially hundreds of millio=
ns of dollars in success. Now, Netflix is saying, <i>You can=E2=80=99t get =
$25 million per year with no incentive to produce popular programming, and =
you also can=E2=80=99t enjoy the upside that comes with popular programming=
 if you=E2=80=99re already making $25 million a year.</i> <br/> <br/>That=
=E2=80=99s at least the thinking. To many, it=E2=80=99s just a
money grab by a company now worth more than $300 billion=E2=80=94a pure fle=
x. Netflix is so much bigger than rivals and is making far more shows and m=
ovies, so it has both the incentive and, importantly, the ability to push c=
osts down. That=E2=80=99s why Sarandos is preaching ratings =E2=80=9Ctransp=
arency,=E2=80=9D as I <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9=
pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dTTWMwWGZCUkhyUVphbWxDMFVJND0iLCJocmVmIjoiaH=
R0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvbmV0ZmxpeC1pcy1hbGwtYWJvdXQtdHJhbnNwYXJlbmN5LW5vdy8_d=
XRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVdoYXQrSSUyN20rSGVhcmluZystK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODklMkYyNiUy=
RjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9V2hhdCtJJTI3bStIZWFyaW5nKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlM=
rJTI4OSUyRjI2JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV=
9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpb=
nRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjEwNDEyODl9/e35cf21a838=
97ad566706ad5f91d48c0ac2cf6e190bd78bac89553bd853f2785" style=3D"color:#d400=
00;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">wrote</a></u> last =
week. And if that means offering a few big backend payouts down the line, i=
t=E2=80=99s a small price to pay for no longer subsidizing the whiffs that =
populate the lower end of the semi-annual Engagement Reports. And, of cours=
e, shutting up the agents behind those whiffs.  <br/> <br/>So far, the new =
contingent compensation system has been deployed only on a few film project=
s. The talent get their fees like usual, but instead of a
buyout of backend there is a contingent element. The ultimate result is tha=
t the star or filmmaker agrees to take, say, 80 cents on the dollar, and if=
 the project hits a certain number of =E2=80=9Cviews=E2=80=9D (defined simi=
larly to what the guilds got in their recent deal, which is a hurdle above =
what the average Netflix project delivers), the participant gets back 40 ce=
nts on those 20 cents they gave up=E2=80=94or possibly more in <i>great</i>=
 success.<br/> <br/>As I=E2=80=99ve written, the new head of business affai=
rs for the film division, <b>Jun Oh</b>, and the Netflix contingent compens=
ation strategy team (yes, that=E2=80=99s a thing), have a goal of eventuall=
y expanding it elsewhere=E2=80=94and, crucially, to get the town on board. =
But it=E2=80=99s clearly designed to reduce costs, which prompted Endeavor =
C.E.O. <b>Ari Emanuel</b> to inelegantly joke with Bajaria in front of ever=
yone on Tuesday, =E2=80=9CWhen are you gonna talk about backend and how you=
=E2=80=99re gonna fuck us?=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
